%description:
Regression test for the RFC 5036 Section 2.8 loop detection feature (commit C4):
hop-count/path-vector TLVs on propagated Label Request messages, ~Ldp.loopDetection
(default false).

Ad hoc 3-LSR triangle (LSR1 -- LSR2 -- LSR3 -- LSR1, all three links directly
connected), built entirely within this .test file (no shipped example has a
topology with an actual forwarding LOOP -- LDPTEST's redundant paths all still
converge to a single egress). Each LSR's hand-written .rt file gives a static
route for one specific external prefix (203.0.113.0/24, TEST-NET-3, deliberately
unreachable/unowned by any of the three) whose next hop cycles: LSR1's route
points at LSR2, LSR2's points at LSR3, LSR3's points back at LSR1 -- a genuine
routing loop for that one prefix. None of the three is ever egress for it, and
none ever holds a real downstream mapping, so ordinary Downstream-on-Demand
(distributionMode="dod", set explicitly here -- the model's DEFAULT is DU, which
never issues a Label Request in the first place and so never exercises this
code path at all) would otherwise let each LSR's Label Request for this FEC
circulate the loop indefinitely.

With loopDetection=true (this file's only config), each LSR that receives a
Label Request for this FEC and holds no downstream mapping of its own now
propagates the request one hop further downstream, carrying an accumulating
Hop Count/Path Vector (RFC 5036 Section 2.8); once the vector has gone all the
way around the triangle it contains the originating LSR's own LSR-ID again, so
that LSR detects the loop, drops the request, and sends back a Notification
(Loop Detected status). Observed: all three LSRs independently originate a
request for this FEC once their own session comes up; before the full 3-session
mesh is OPERATIONAL, an LSR can transiently misjudge itself "egress" for the
looping FEC (its own downstream session not being up YET is indistinguishable,
via findPeerSocket(), from genuinely having no downstream peer) and reply with a
real (wrong) mapping -- a pre-existing DoD/session-establishment race, nothing
to do with loop detection itself. This self-corrects once the missing session
comes up (Ldp::updateFecListEntry withdraws the stale upstream mapping and
re-requests downstream); once the whole mesh is OPERATIONAL, every further
attempt correctly takes the propagate-downstream path and the accumulating
vector eventually trips isLoopDetected(). So this test asserts the Loop Detected
line, AND separately (scoped to everything from the first such line onward, via
a postrun awk filter) that no FURTHER Label Mapping for this FEC ever appears
once loop detection has caught it -- rather than "never", which the transient
race above would make false.

The counterpart file ldp_loop_detection_disabled.test runs the identical
network/scenario with loopDetection=false and documents/asserts what happens
instead (no propagation, no Notification -- see that file for what was actually
observed).

Falsification: this test FAILS against the parent commit -- loopDetection does
not exist there (unknown parameter), and even stashing just the .ned addition
back in (to let the ini parse) the "Loop Detected" line can never appear since
no code path sends it.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LoopTriangle.ned

import inet.node.mpls.LdpMplsRouter;

//
// Ad hoc 3-LSR triangle, all links directly connected: LSR1 -- LSR2 -- LSR3 -- LSR1.
// See the .test file's %description for the routing-loop static configuration.
//
network LoopTriangle
{
    parameters:
        **.ipv4.configurator.networkConfiguratorModule = "";
    submodules:
        LSR1: LdpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=200,150");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR2: LdpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,100");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR3: LdpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,250");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
    connections:
        LSR1.pppg[0] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 1Mbps; } <--> LSR2.pppg[0];
        LSR2.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 1Mbps; } <--> LSR3.pppg[0];
        LSR3.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 1Mbps; } <--> LSR1.pppg[1];
}

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Addressing: LSR1.ppp0=10.0.1.1 <-> LSR2.ppp0=10.0.1.2 (link A)
%#             LSR2.ppp1=10.0.2.1 <-> LSR3.ppp0=10.0.2.2 (link B)
%#             LSR3.ppp1=10.0.3.1 <-> LSR1.ppp1=10.0.3.2 (link C)
%# routerId="auto" (default) picks the HIGHEST interface address per LSR:
%#   LSR1 routerId = max(10.0.1.1, 10.0.3.2) = 10.0.3.2
%#   LSR2 routerId = max(10.0.1.2, 10.0.2.1) = 10.0.2.1
%#   LSR3 routerId = max(10.0.2.2, 10.0.3.1) = 10.0.3.1
%# The routing-loop route's gateway is always the NEXT HOP's routerId (that is what
%# Ldp::rebuildFecList treats as the FEC's next hop / LDP peer identity).
%file: LSR1.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.1.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.3.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.2.1	10.0.1.2	255.255.255.255	G	0	ppp0
10.0.3.1	10.0.3.1	255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp1
203.0.113.0	10.0.2.1	255.255.255.0	G	0	ppp0

224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR2.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.1.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.2.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.3.2	10.0.1.1	255.255.255.255	G	0	ppp0
10.0.3.1	10.0.2.2	255.255.255.255	G	0	ppp1
203.0.113.0	10.0.3.1	255.255.255.0	G	0	ppp1

224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR3.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.2.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.3.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.2.1	10.0.2.1	255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
10.0.3.2	10.0.3.2	255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp1
203.0.113.0	10.0.3.2	255.255.255.0	G	0	ppp1

224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%inifile: test.ini

[General]
ned-path = .;../../../../src
network = LoopTriangle
sim-time-limit = 10s
total-stack = 64MiB
record-vector-results = false
cmdenv-express-mode = false
cmdenv-event-banners = false
**.ldp.cmdenv-log-level = detail
**.cmdenv-log-level = off
output-scalar-file = "${resultdir}/${configname}-#${runnumber}.sca"

**.LSR1.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR1.rt"
**.LSR2.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR2.rt"
**.LSR3.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR3.rt"

# Ted::rebuildRoutingTable() otherwise unconditionally recomputes/overwrites every
# non-multicast route from its own link-state view (installRoutes default true) --
# this test needs its own hand-written routes (including the deliberate routing
# LOOP) to actually stick, so this LSR-only concern (LDP's own peer/session
# discovery and TED link tracking are unaffected -- see Ted.ned) is disabled here.
**.ted.installRoutes = false

**.ppp[*].queue.typename = "DropTailQueue"
**.ppp[*].queue.packetCapacity = 10

**.holdTime = 3s
**.helloInterval = 1s

**.ldp.distributionMode = "dod"
**.ldp.loopDetection = true

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# the accumulating hop-count/path-vector eventually detects the loop and drops/notifies;
%# fires once per LSR (each is the "loop closes back on me" point for its own originated
%# request) with hopCount=3 (one increment per hop all the way around the triangle)
%contains-regex: stdout
Loop Detected in Label Request for fec=addr=203\.0\.113\.0  length=24 from \S+ \(hopCount=3, pathVectorLimit=32\)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# once loop detection has caught on (first such line onward), no FURTHER Label Mapping
%# for the looping FEC ever appears -- unlike "never" over the WHOLE run, which would be
%# false: an early, pre-existing DoD/session-establishment race (an LSR whose own
%# downstream session isn't OPERATIONAL yet is indistinguishable from "no downstream
%# peer" via findPeerSocket(), so it transiently misjudges itself egress) does let one
%# real (wrong) mapping through per LSR before the full mesh converges -- self-corrected
%# via Withdraw/re-request, nothing to do with loop detection itself (see %description)
%postrun-command: awk '/Loop Detected in Label Request for fec=addr=203\.0\.113\.0/{p=1} p' test.out > after_loop_detected.out
%not-contains: after_loop_detected.out
Label mapping label=
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
